# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fauna-db
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:fauna-db/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:fauna-db/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Spanner stores large amounts of mutable structured data.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Spanner allows users to perform arbitrary queries using SQL with relational data while maintaining strong consistency and high availability for that data with synchronous replication.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Spanner was first described in 2012 for internal Google data centers.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Spanner's SQL capability was added in 2017 and documented in a SIGMOD 2017 paper.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] It became available as part of Google Cloud Platform in 2017, under the name "Cloud Spanner".
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Spanner uses the Paxos algorithm as part of its operation to shard (partition) data across up to hundreds of servers.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] It makes heavy use of hardware-assisted clock synchronization using GPS clocks and atomic clocks to ensure global consistency.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] TrueTime is the brand name for Google's distributed cloud infrastructure, which provides Spanner with the ability to generate monotonically increasing timestamps in data centers around the world.
[src:fauna-db/google-spanner] Google's F1 SQL database management system (DBMS) is built on top of Spanner, replacing Google's custom MySQL variant.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] This driver can only be used with FQL v10, and is not compatible with earlier versions of FQL.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To query your databases with earlier API versions, see the faunadb package.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] See the Fauna Documentation for additional information on how to configure and query your databases.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] API reference documentation for the driver is available at https://fauna.github.io/fauna-js/.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] You can install it using your preferred package manager.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] By default, the driver's `Client` instance authenticates with Fauna using an access token in the `FAUNA_SECRET` environment variable.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If needed, you can pass the token to the client using the `secret` argument instead.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The `fql` function is your gateway to building safe, reuseable Fauna queries.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] It allows you compose queries from sub-queries and variables native to your program.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Variables passed in are treated as unexecutable values in Fauna's API - preventing security issues like injection attacks.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] With TypeScript, you can apply a type parameter to your result.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Alternatively, you can apply a type parameter directly to your fql statements and `Client` methods will infer your return types.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Due to backwards compatibility, if a type parameter is provided to `Client` methods, it will override the inferred type from your query.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To use a custom interface as a query response, extend the `QueryValueObject` interface.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Options are available to configure queries on each request.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] These override any default query options in the client configuration.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Query statistics are returned with successful query responses and errors of the `ServiceError` type.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Use `paginate()` to iterate sets that contain more than one page of results.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] `paginate()` accepts the same query options as `query()`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The driver's `Client` instance comes with reasonable defaults that should be used in most cases.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] You can override these defaults if needed.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] In addition to configuring the client, you can also set default query options.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The driver will default to configuring your client with the values of the `FAUNA_SECRET` and `FAUNA_ENDPOINT` environment variable.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The maximum number of times a query will be attempted if a retryable exception is thrown (ThrottlingError).
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Default 3, inclusive of the initial call.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The retry strategy implemented is a simple exponential backoff.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To disable retries, pass max_attempts less than or equal to 1.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The maximum backoff in seconds to be observed between each retry.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] There are a few different timeout settings that can be configured; each comes with a default setting.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] We recommend that most applications simply stick to the defaults.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The query timeout is the time, in milliseconds, that Fauna will spend executing your query before aborting with a 503 Timeout error.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If a query timeout occurs, the driver will throw an instance of `QueryTimeoutError`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The query timeout can be set using the `query_timeout_ms` client configuration option.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The default value if you do not provide one is 5000 ms (5 seconds).
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The query timeout can also be set to a different value for each query using the `query_timeout_ms` query option.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Doing so overrides the client configuration when performing this query.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The client timeout is the time, in milliseconds, that the client will wait for a network response before canceling the request.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If a client timeout occurs, the driver will throw an instance of `NetworkError`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The client timeout is always the query timeout plus an additional buffer.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] This ensures that the client always waits for at least as long Fauna could work on your query and account for network latency.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The client timeout buffer is configured by setting the `client_timeout_buffer_ms` option.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The default value for the buffer if you do not provide on is 5000 ms (5 seconds), therefore the default client timeout is 10000 ms (10 s) when considering the default query timeout.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The HTTP/2 session idle timeout is the time, in milliseconds, that an HTTP/2 session will remain open after there is no more pending communication.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Once the session idle time has elapsed the session is considered idle and the session is closed.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Subsequent requests will create a new session; the session idle timeout does not result in an error.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Configure the HTTP/2 session idle timeout using the `http2_session_idle_ms` option.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] This setting only applies to clients using HTTP/2 implementations; for example, the default client for Node.js runtimes.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] An event feed asynchronously polls an event source for events.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To get an event source, append `eventSource()` or `eventsOn()` to a supported Set.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If changes occur between the creation of the event source and the `feed()` request, the feed replays and emits any related events.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If you pass an event source query to `feed()`, the driver creates the event source and requests the event feed at the same time.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] `feed()` returns a `FeedClient` instance that can act as an `AsyncIterator`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] This distinction allows for you to ignore errors originating from event processing.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The client configuration sets the default options for `feed()`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] You can reuse cursors across event sources with identical queries in the same database.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To get an event source, append `eventSource()` or `eventsOn()` to a set from a supported source.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] The client configuration sets default options for the `stream()` method.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] For supported properties, see StreamClientConfiguration in the API reference.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If `FAUNA_DEBUG` is not set or is invalid, logging is disabled.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Any contributions from the community are greatly appreciated!
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If you have a suggestion that would make this better, please fork the repo and create a pull request.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] We provide templates, so please complete those to the best of your ability.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Don't forget to give the project a star!
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] This will start local fauna containers, verify they're up and run all tests.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] In cases where you are modifying types and need to test type enforcement, you can use `@ts-expect-error`.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Using `@ts-expect-error` will supress any type errors on the following line.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Conversely, if there's no error, TypeScript will report its usage as not being neccessary.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] To learn more about `@ts-expect-error`, you can read more about it in the TypeScript release notes.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] Linting runs automatically on each commit.
[src:fauna-db/main-readme-md] If you wish to run on-demand run `yarn lint`.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:fauna-db/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:fauna-db/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In the fields of databases and transaction processing (transaction management), a **schedule** (or **history**) of a system is an abstract model to describe the order of executions in a set of transactions running in the system.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Often it is a *list* of operations (actions) ordered by time, performed by a set of transactions that are executed together in the system.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] If the order in time between certain operations is not determined by the system, then a *partial order* is used.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Examples of such operations are requesting a read operation, reading, writing, aborting, committing, requesting a lock, locking, etc.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Often, only a subset of the transaction operation types are included in a schedule.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Schedules are fundamental concepts in database concurrency control theory.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In practice, most general purpose database systems employ conflict-serializable and strict recoverable schedules.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Alternatively, a schedule can be represented with a *directed acyclic graph* (or DAG) in which there is an arc (i.e., directed edge) between each *ordered pair* of operations.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In this example, the columns represent the different transactions in the schedule D.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Schedule D consists of three transactions T1, T2, T3.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] First T1 Reads and Writes to object X, and then Commits.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Then T2 Reads and Writes to object Y and Commits, and finally, T3 Reads and Writes to object Z and Commits.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Usually, for the purpose of reasoning about concurrency control in databases, an operation is modelled as *atomic*, occurring at a point in time, without duration.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Real executed operations always have some duration.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Operations of transactions in a schedule can interleave (i.e., transactions can be executed concurrently), but time orders between operations in each transaction must remain unchanged.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The schedule is in *partial order* when the operations of transactions in a schedule interleave (i.e., when the schedule is conflict-serializable but not serial).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The schedule is in *total order* when the operations of transactions in a schedule do not interleave (i.e., when the schedule is serial).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A **complete schedule** is one that contains either an abort (a.k.a.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] **rollback)** or commit action for each of its transactions.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A transaction's last action is either to commit or abort.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] To maintain atomicity, a transaction must undo all its actions if it is aborted.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule is **serial** if the executed transactions are non-interleaved (i.e., a serial schedule is one in which no transaction starts until a running transaction has ended).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule is **serializable** if it is equivalent (in its outcome) to a serial schedule.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In schedule E, the order in which the actions of the transactions are executed is not the same as in D, but in the end, E gives the same result as D.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Serializability is used to keep the data in the data item in a consistent state.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] It is the major criterion for the correctness of concurrent transactions' schedule, and thus supported in all general purpose database systems.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Schedules that are not serializable are likely to generate erroneous outcomes; which can be extremely harmful (e.g., when dealing with money within banks).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] If any specific order between some transactions is requested by an application, then it is enforced independently of the underlying serializability mechanisms.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] These mechanisms are typically indifferent to any specific order, and generate some unpredictable partial order that is typically compatible with multiple serial orders of these transactions.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] At least one of the actions is a write operation.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The actions access the same object (read or write).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Equivalently, two actions are considered conflicting if and only if they are noncommutative.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Equivalently, two actions are considered conflicting if and only if they are a read-write, write-read, or write-write conflict.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Reducing conflicts, such as through commutativity, enhances performance because conflicts are the fundamental cause of delays and aborts.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Both schedules have the same set of conflicting pairs (such that the actions in each conflicting pair are in the same order).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] This is equivalent to requiring that all conflicting operations (i.e., operations in any conflicting pair) are in the same order in both schedules.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Equivalently, two schedules are said to be conflict equivalent if and only if one can be transformed to another by swapping pairs of non-conflicting operations (whether adjacent or not) while maintaining the order of actions for each transaction.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Equivalently, two schedules are said to be conflict equivalent if and only if one can be transformed to another by swapping pairs of non-conflicting adjacent operations with different transactions.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule is said to be **conflict-serializable** when the schedule is conflict-equivalent to one or more serial schedules.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Equivalently, a schedule is conflict-serializable if and only if its precedence graph is acyclic when only committed transactions are considered.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Note that if the graph is defined to also include uncommitted transactions, then cycles involving uncommitted transactions may occur without conflict serializability violation.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The schedule K is conflict-equivalent to the serial schedule <T1,T2>, but not <T2,T1>.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Conflict serializability can be enforced by restarting any transaction within the cycle in the precedence graph, or by implementing two-phase locking, timestamp ordering, or serializable snapshot isolation.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] If the transaction $T_{i}$ reads a value (for an object X) written by the transaction $T_{j}$ in S1, it must do so in S2.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] If the transaction $T_{i}$ in S1 does the final write for object X, so does the same transaction $T_{i}$ in S2.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Additionally, two view-equivalent schedules must involve the same set of transactions such that each transaction has the same actions in the same order.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In the example below, the schedules S1 and S2 are view-equivalent, but neither S1 nor S2 are view-equivalent to the schedule S3.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Failed the second condition of view equivalence because T2 read the value written by T1 for B in S1 and S2, but T1 read the value written by T2 for B in S3.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Failed the third condition of view equivalence because T2 did the final write for B in S1 and S2, but T1 did the final write for B in S3.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] To quickly analyze whether two schedules are view-equivalent, write both schedules as a list with each action's subscript representing which view-equivalence condition they match.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule is **view-serializable** if it is view-equivalent to some serial schedule.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Note that by definition, all conflict-serializable schedules are view-serializable.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Notice that the above example (which is the same as the example in the discussion of conflict-serializable) is both view-serializable and conflict-serializable at the same time.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The above example is not conflict-serializable, but it is view-serializable since it has a view-equivalent serial schedule <T1,| T2,| T3>.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Since determining whether a schedule is view-serializable is NP-complete, view-serializability has little practical interest.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In a **recoverable schedule**, transactions only commit after all transactions whose changes they read have committed.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule becomes **unrecoverable** if a transaction $T_{i}$ reads and relies on changes from another transaction $T_{j}$ , and then $T_{i}$ commits and $T_{j}$ aborts.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The schedule F is recoverable because T1 commits before T2, that makes the value read by T2 correct.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In the F2 schedule, if T1 aborted, T2 has to abort because the value of A it read is incorrect.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In both cases, the database is left in a consistent state.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Schedule J is unrecoverable because T2 committed before T1 despite previously reading the value written by T1.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Because T1 aborted after T2 committed, the value read by T2 is wrong.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Because a transaction cannot be rolled-back after it commits, the schedule is unrecoverable.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] In this example, although F2 is recoverable, it does not avoid cascading aborts.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] It can be seen that if T1 aborts, T2 will have to be aborted too in order to maintain the correctness of the schedule as T2 has already read the uncommitted value written by T1.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The following is a recoverable schedule which avoids cascading abort.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Note, however, that the update of A by T1 is always lost (since T1 is aborted).
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Note that this Schedule would not be serializable if T1 would be committed.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Cascading aborts avoidance is sufficient but not necessary for a schedule to be recoverable.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] A schedule is **strict** if for any two transactions T1, T2, if a write operation of T1 precedes a *conflicting* operation of T2 (either read or write), then the commit or abort event of T1 also precedes that conflicting operation of T2.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] For example, the schedule F3 above is strict.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Any strict schedule is cascade-less, but not the converse.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] Strictness allows efficient recovery of databases from failure.
[src:fauna-db/serializability] The Venn diagram (below) illustrates the above clauses graphically.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:fauna-db/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
